reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The slp-vectorizer horizontally reduces a chain of boolean logic selects (logical and/or encoded as select patterns). It reassociates and may reorder operands. With LLVM poison semantics, this is not freely associative: reordering can expose a previously gated poison value. In the reproducer, the original scalar sequence gates a potentially poison %c1 using %1 first (s1 = select %1, %c1, false). The vectorizer reorders so it first gates %c1 with %c3 (select %c3, %c1, false). If %c1 is poison, %1 is false, and %c3 is true, the transformed code selects poison, while the original returned false. This is reported by Alive2 as "Target is more poisonous than source".

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
- The pass identifies a horizontal reduction and vectorizes it. It introduces a freeze on %c3:
  %2 = freeze i1 %c3
  %op.rdx = select i1 %2, i1 %c1, i1 false
  %op.rdx1 = select i1 %op.rdx, i1 %1, i1 false
- Alive2 shows the target produces poison when %c1 is poison and %1=false, %c3=true. The original yields false since %1 was the initial guard.
- The first transformation point is HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce(). The helper GetNewVectorizedTree at lines ~19819–19847 attempts to pick which operand to feed as LHS for boolean reductions, using ReducedValsToOps and a fallback freeze of VectorizedTree. That freeze is only on the condition-like operand, not on the RHS; thus it doesn't prevent poison leaking when the order makes a RHS-only candidate selected early.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
- For boolean logic reductions (select-based logical and/or), the short-circuit-like gating order matters for poison safety. The current algorithm may begin combining two values that were never used as the select condition (operand 0) in any original scalar op. This can select a previously gated poison RHS earlier than in the original program.
- The current freeze logic in GetNewVectorizedTree is insufficient because freezing the would-be condition doesn't stop the RHS from being selected early.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
- Insertion point: line 19933 (immediately after the shuffled-extracts block and before the "Emit code for constant values" section within HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce()).
- Change: Stable-reorder the local Candidates vector for boolean logic reductions so that we start combining from values that originally served as the select condition (operand 0) of any boolean logic op. This preserves the original gating and prevents early exposure of RHS-only poison values.
- Suggested code to insert at line 19933:
  // Prefer starting boolean logic reductions from values that originally
  // appeared as the select condition (operand 0). This preserves the
  // short-circuit gating order and avoids exposing poison from RHS-only
  // operands when we reassociate the reduction.
  if (AnyBoolLogicOp && Candidates.size() > 1) {
    auto IsLHSInBoolOp = [&](Value *V) {
      auto It = ReducedValsToOps.find(V);
      if (It == ReducedValsToOps.end())
        return false;
      return any_of(It->second, [&](Instruction *I) {
        return isBoolLogicOp(I) && getRdxOperand(I, /*Index=*/0) == V;
      });
    };
    SmallVector<Value *> LHSFirst, Others;
    LHSFirst.reserve(Candidates.size());
    Others.reserve(Candidates.size());
    for (Value *V : Candidates)
      (IsLHSInBoolOp(V) ? LHSFirst : Others).push_back(V);
    // Only reorder if both partitions are non-empty.
    if (!LHSFirst.empty() && LHSFirst.size() != Candidates.size()) {
      SmallVector<Value *> NewOrder;
      NewOrder.reserve(Candidates.size());
      NewOrder.append(LHSFirst.begin(), LHSFirst.end());
      NewOrder.append(Others.begin(), Others.end());
      Candidates.swap(NewOrder);
    }
  }

This leverages the existing ReducedValsToOps map and helper predicates isBoolLogicOp/getRdxOperand(). It is a local, minimal change that only touches the boolean logic path.

Alternative considered but not chosen: Freeze both operands when creating boolean reductions. This is safe but over-conservative and may pessimize codegen.

5. Conclusion:
The bug is due to operand reordering in boolean logic horizontal reductions, which can violate poison-safe gating. The fix is to bias the candidate order for boolean reductions to start from values used as select conditions (operand 0) in the original code, preserving the gating order and avoiding the poison leak. This should make the transformed IR poison-safe and fix the provided reproducer without impacting non-boolean reductions.

